et_option linter.unusedVariables false\nnoncomputable section\n\n/-! # Exercises to practice -/\n\nsection\n\n/- There are special cases of the change of variables theorems for affine transformations\n(but you can also use the change of variable theorem from the lecture) -/\nexample (a b : ℝ) :\n    ∫ x in a..b, sin (x / 2 + 3) =\n    2 * cos (a / 2 + 3) - 2 * cos (b / 2  + 3) := by\n```\n\nNow we need to compute the integral $\\int_a^b \\sin(x/2 + 3) \\, dx$.\n\nTo compute this integral, we can use the substitution $u = x/2 + 3$, which gives $du = (1/2)dx$, so $dx = 2du$.\n\nTherefore, $\\int \\sin(u) \\cdot 2du = 2 \\int \\sin(u) du = 2(-\\cos(u)) + C = -2\\cos(u) + C = -2\\cos(x/2 + 3) + C$.\n\nSo the antiderivative is $-2\\cos(x/2 + 3)$.\n\nTherefore, $\\int_a^b \\sin(x/2 + 3) \\, dx = [-2\\cos(x/2 + 3)]_a^b = -2\\cos(b/2 + 3) - (-2\\cos(a/2 + 3)) = -2\\cos(b/2 + 3) + 2\\cos(a/2 + 3) = 2\\cos(a/2 + 3) - 2\\cos(b/2 + 3)$.\n\nThis is exactly the right-hand side of the equation.\n\nIn Lean 4, we can compute this integral using the fundamental theorem of calculus. Let's try to prove it.\n\n```tactics\n  have h1 : ∫ x in a..b, sin (x / 2 + 3) = 2 * cos (a / 2 + 3) - 2 * cos (b / 2 + 3) := by\n```\n\nNow we need to compute the integral. Let's use the fundamental theorem of calculus.\n\nWe need to show that the integral from a to b of sin(x/2 + 3) dx is equal to the right-hand side.\n\nTo compute the integral, we can use the antiderivative we found: -2*cos(x/2 + 3).\n\nSo in Lean 4, we can use the fundamental theorem of calculus:\n\n```tactics\n    simp [intervalIntegral.integral_const, add_mul, mul_add, mul_comm]\n    <;> ring_nf\n    <;> simp [sin_add, cos_add]\n    <;> ring\n```\n\nWait, let's think more carefully. The integral of sin(x/2 + 3) from a to b.\n\nLet's compute it directly using Lean's calculus.\n\nWe can use the fundamental theorem of calculus. Let's define the antiderivative function.\n\nLet $F(x) = -2*cos(x/2 + 3)$.\n\nThen $F'(x) = -2*(-sin(x/2 + 3)*(1/2)) = -2*(- (1/2)*sin(x/2 + 3)) = -2*(- (1/2)*sin(x/2 + 3)) = sin(x/2 + 3)$.\n\nTherefore, $F(x)$ is indeed the antiderivative.\n\nTherefore, $\\int_a^b sin(x/2 + 3) dx = F(b) - F(a) = (-2*cos(b/2 + 3)) - (-2*cos(a/2 + 3)) = (-2*cos(b/2 + 3)) + 2*cos(a/2 + 3) = 2*cos(a/2 + 3) - 2*cos(b/2 + 3)$.\n\nSo in Lean 4, we need to use the fundamental theorem of calculus. Let's try to compute it directly.\n\n```tactics\n  exact h1\n```\n\nWait, perhaps we need a more direct approach. Let's try to compute the integral using Lean's calculus.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Integrals.Basic\nimport Mathlib.RingTheory.Real.Irrational\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Convolution\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Integral.Prod\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Function.JacobianOneDim\n\nopen BigOperators Function Set Real Topology Filter\nopen ENNReal MeasureTheory Interval intervalIntegral\nset_option linter.unusedVariables false\nnoncomputable section\n\n/-! # Exercises to practice -/\n\nsection\n\n/- There are special cases of the change of variables theorems for affine transformations\n(but you can also use the change of variable theorem from the lecture) -/\nexample (a b : ℝ) :\n    ∫ x in a..b, sin (x / 2 + 3) =\n    2 * cos (a / 2 + 3) - 2 * cos (b / 2  + 3) := by\n```\n\nNow we need to compute the integral $\\int_a^b \\sin(x/2 + 3) \\, dx$.\n\nTo compute this integral, we can use the substitution $u = x/2 + 3$, which gives $du = (1/2)dx$, so $dx = 2du$.\n\nTherefore, $\\int \\sin(u) \\cdot 2du = 2 \\int \\sin(u) du = 2(-\\cos(u)) + C = -2\\cos(u) + C = -2\\cos(x/2 + 3) + C$.\n\nSo the antiderivative is $-2\\cos(x/2 + 3)$.\n\nTherefore, $\\int_a^b \\sin(x/2 + 3) \\, dx = [-2\\cos(x/2 + 3)]_a^b = -2\\cos(b/2 + 3) - (-2\\cos(a/2 + 3)) = -2\\cos(b/2 + 3) + 2\\cos(a/2 + 3) = 2\\cos(a/2 + 3) - 2\\cos(b/2 + 3)$.\n\nThis is exactly the right-hand side of the equation.\n\nIn Lean 4, we can compute this integral using the fundamental theorem of calculus. Let's try to prove 