      "\n    ∫ x in a..b, sin (x / 2 + 3) =\n    2 * cos (a / 2 + 3) - 2 * cos (b / 2  + 3) := by\n```\n\nNow we need to compute the integral. In calculus, we would find the antiderivative. Let's compute it manually first:\n\nThe integral of $\\sin(x/2 + 3)$ with respect to $x$.\n\nLet $u = x/2 + 3$, then $du/dx = 1/2$, so $dx = 2 du$.\n\nTherefore, $\\sin(u) \\cdot 2 du = 2 \\sin(u) du$.\n\nThe integral of $\\sin(u)$ is $-\\cos(u)$, so the integral is $2(-\\cos(u)) + C = -2\\cos(u) + C = -2\\cos(x/2 + 3) + C$.\n\nTherefore, the definite integral from $a$ to $b$ is:\n\n$[-2\\cos(x/2 + 3)]_a^b = -2\\cos(b/2 + 3) - (-2\\cos(a/2 + 3)) = -2\\cos(b/2 + 3) + 2\\cos(a/2 + 3) = 2\\cos(a/2 + 3) - 2\\cos(b/2 + 3)$.\n\nThis is the desired result. In Lean, we need to use appropriate tactics. Let's try:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Integrals.Basic\nimport Mathlib.RingTheory.Real.Irrational\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Convolution\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Integral.Prod\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Function.JacobianOneDim\n\nopen BigOperators Function Set Real Topology Filter\nopen ENNReal MeasureTheory Interval intervalIntegral\nset_option linter.unusedVariables false\nnoncomputable section\n\n/-! # Exercises to practice -/\n\nsection\n\n/- There are special cases of the change of variables theorems for affine transformations\n(but you can also use the change of variable theorem from the lecture) -/\nexample (a b : ℝ) :\n    ∫ x in a..b, sin (x / 2 + 3) =\n    2 * cos (a / 2 + 3) - 2 * cos (b / 2  + 3) := by\n```\n\nWe can try to compute the integral directly. Let's see if Lean's calculus can handle this directly.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Integrals.Basic\nimport Mathlib.RingTheory.Real.Irrational\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Convolution\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Integral.Prod\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Function.JacobianOneDim\n\nopen BigOperators Function Set Real Topology Filter\nopen ENNReal MeasureTheory Interval i