section

/- There are special cases of the change of variables theorems for affine transformations
(but you can also use the change of variable theorem from the lecture) -/
example (a b : ℝ) :
    ∫ x in a..b, sin (x / 2 + 3) =
    2 * cos (a / 2 + 3) - 2 * cos (b / 2  + 3) := by
```

To compute $\int_a^b \sin(x/2 + 3) dx$, we can use the fundamental theorem of calculus. The antiderivative is $-2\cos(x/2 + 3)$.

So $\int_a^b \sin(x/2 + 3) dx = [-2\cos(x/2 + 3)]_a^b = -2\cos(b/2 + 3) - (-2\cos(a/2 + 3)) = -2\cos(b/2 + 3) + 2\cos(a/2 + 3) = 2\cos(a/2 + 3) - 2\cos(b/2 + 3)$.

In Lean, we can use `norm_num` and appropriate lemmas.

