Using substitution: let $u = x/2 + 3$, then $du = (1/2)dx$, so $dx = 2du$. Then $\sin(u) \cdot 2 du = 2\sin(u) du$. The integral of $\sin(u)$ is $-\cos(u)$, so the integral is $2(-\cos(u)) + C = -2\cos(u) + C = -2\cos(x/2 + 3) + C$.

Applying the fundamental theorem of calculus: $[-2\cos(x/2 + 3)]_a^b = -2\cos(b/2 + 3) - (-2\cos(a/2 + 3)) = -2\cos(b/2 + 3) + 2\cos(a/2 + 3) = 2\cos(a/2 + 3) - 2\cos(b/2 + 3)$.

